skeleton of github actions
name:
on: [push]
jobs:
  build:  -- build job 
	runs-on: ubuntu-latest - default free agent provided by github action
    steps:
	  - name: step name
	    uses: 'uses' is to call github action plugins. for ex. actions/checkout@v3
	  - name: step2
	    run: run is to run the shell commands directly
  test: -- test job
	runs-on: ubuntu-latest
	needs: build -- run jobs sequentially
	steps: 
	- name: step 1
	  run: |
		echo "running multi line shell commands"
		

steps will run sequentially. jobs will run parallely
whatever file you generate during the workflow execute will be saved in github runner machine. it will be lost once the workflow execution finishes. we have to upload to artifact to package n upload to github's storage. 

trigger options: push, pull_request, schedule, release, issues
workflow_dispatch - manual trigger
repository_dispatch - api call trigger
workflow_call - allow one workflow to call another workflow 
workflow_run - trigger deploy workflow when build workflow completed

in workflow_dispatch we can add inputs while trigger and can enable/disable jobs during execution
on: 
   workflow_dispatch:
     input:
	   environment: -- param name
	     description: "some description"
		 required: true
		 default: "staging" -- default value
jobs:
 deploy:
	runs-on: ubuntu-latest
	if: ${{ github.event.inputs.environment == "staging" }}
    steps:
    - name: step 1
      if: ${{ github.event.inputs.environment == "staging" }}
	  run: ...
	  
this input option at execution only available for manual trigger. further ways to control workflow is to add
1)env variable.. declared with 
env:
  DEPLOY: "prod"
access using $DEPLOY
2)secrets.. stored at repo or org level and accessed using
env:
  API_KEY: ${{ secrets.MY_API_KEY }}
3)github context / event payload / runtime variables available on the workflow.
accessed using
if: ${{ github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'  }} - triggers job / step only if the branch is main
github.event_name - on which action its triggered push / push req ...
github.sha - commit sha value
github.actor - who triggered
github.run_number - build number

GITHUB_TOKEN - built in secret in github. it can be used when workflow wants to access github like push code, create branch, releases, etc..
By default, GITHUB_TOKEN has read/write access to the repo
You can restrict or expand its permissions in your workflow:
permissions:
  contents: write   # allow pushing commits
  issues: write     # allow commenting on issues
  pull-requests: read
  id-token: write   # related to OIDC. tells Github actions that this workflow is allowed to request an OIDC token from GitHub’s identity provider.
  actions: read # allow getting workflows run details, write allows trigger / cancel other workflows
  
environments are job level. we can specify variables, secrets and add reviewers and access them inside the jobs

github runners comes with preinstalled softwares. self hosted runners should have all the packages n tools installed for the jobs to work. so we can use containers as runtime for the self hosted runners. 
	
commonly used github actions:
actions/checkout@v3
actions/setup-java , setup-python, setup-node
actions/upload-artifact , download-artifact - retrieves artifacts in later job
docker/build-push-action - builds and pushes Docker images

upload-artifact is for sharing files b/w jobs in same workflow. output artifact is only to share values b/w jobs in same workflow
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    outputs:
      artifact-path: ${{ steps.save.outputs.path }}
    steps:
      - id: save
        run: echo "path=output/message.txt" >> $GITHUB_OUTPUT

  deploy:
    needs: build
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - run: echo "Deploying from ${{ needs.build.outputs.artifact-path }}"

concurrency: → prevent duplicate runs (e.g., cancel old runs if new commit arrives).
concurrency: ci-${{ github.ref }}
Cache speeds up workflows by reusing dependencies or build outputs between runs. - actions/cache@v3

